Palestine says to Israel: We will break all existing agreements
Palestinian President Mahmud Abbas announced on Thursday at a UN General Assembly session that he would break any agreements with Israel if the country’s future government tried to meet Benjamin Netanyahu’s announcement of the annexation of the occupied Palestinian lands.
“If the future government of Israel, which will arise, comes to the realization of this plan, we will cancel all signed agreements (with Israel) and withdraw from all commitments made,” he said.
“We will reject the whole plan completely and completely,” Abbas said.
\"It is our duty to defend all our rights with every possible means - little importance, which will be the consequences - fully involved in the application of international law and in the fight against terrorism,\" said the president of the Palestinian Authority, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, Israel’s premier, was re-elected after the 17 September elections to form a government.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and would include all Jewish settlements throughout the West Bank.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, led by Yasser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements to which the United States was patronized.
The 84-year-old Abbas also promised the United Nations General Assembly to hold universal elections on the land of Palestine.
The last was held in 2006.
“After returning to the country, I will convene local elections in the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem, and all who oppose them will have to be responsible for their actions before God and the international community,” he said.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer at the UN, to exercise the powers of \"full members of the UN and all its bodies and institutions.\"
The Palestinian leader ended the speech by calling on the international community to “force Israel to fulfill with all due respect the provisions of the United Nations”
Israel’s ambassador Danny Danon responded briefly to Abbas’ speech, declaring that the Palestinian leader “will focus at the UN on the efforts of the Palestinian Authority against Israel rather than fighting the calls to terrorism in autonomy under his leadership.”
Danon, as reported by the agencies, did not, however, refer to Netanyahu’s annexation of the occupied Palestinian lands.
