PLN 105 million for video game companies from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of funding will go to companies in the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced on Friday the results of the third edition of the GameINN program.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by the NCBR, there was the development of a platform for creating field games based on the AR game engine creating a real-world map along with an application that allows users to transfer data; a test-training platform for verifying practical skills at work and professional improvement using VR and AI technology; an innovative game simulating real-life production process management using an innovative model of virtual-world interaction with the real-world concept of industry 4.0.
The goal of the GameINN sector program is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game producers in the global market by 2023.
According to the NBBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% a year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, and the forecast for 2019 is 2.23 billion.
“The specially prepared research agenda of GameINN and the already 300 million PLN of support for entrepreneurs under this sector program is an important driver for the further dynamic growth of Polish gamedev,” the statement reads.
The video game industry is an excellent example of the effective exploitation of the potential we have in Poland.
“The government-led incentives for innovative entrepreneurs, such as R&D reliefs, competence improvement programmes, IP boxing, and support programmes carried out by the NCBR drive innovative business and allow them to compete more effectively in a highly competitive market,” said Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the Communication.
The head of the science department points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of funding projects, but also remains in their pockets - with the relief of the R&D in 2018, three-quarters more entrepreneurs than the year before.
“The amount of deducted costs related to R&D’s activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in more than PLN 300 million savings for companies benefiting from this relief.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by the NCBR in three editions of GameINN,” said the Deputy Prime Minister.
The director of the NBBR dr. engineer Wojciech Kamiecki reminds that 78 innovative projects were awarded in the two previous co-financing competitions with a total value of more than PLN 211.2 million.
The huge interest of the third competition and the variety of proposals submitted show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantage.
“In particular, the fact that among the selected projects - as in previous editions - there are projects for solutions for not only entertainment, but also related to industry 4.0 - adds.
In the third GameINN competition for funding of up to PLN 20 million, entrepreneurs, a consortium of entrepreneurs and a consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply.
87 applications for the total amount of co-financing of PLN 317 million were affected by the NCB.
The budget of the competition at the time of the contest was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, thanks to which 27 projects were awarded almost PLN 105 million of funding.
Detailed information about the results of the 3rd GameINN competition is available on the website ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sector program is implemented under the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to the initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Game Agreement, including companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
