According to a report published by GUS on household budgets on Friday, 44 per cent of households have evaluated their material situation as good or rather good.
The previous year was 37.2%, 33.5% in 2016 and before, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of the situation of households, it never exceeded 30%.
In total, 8.1% of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2% a year earlier and more than 20% in 2009.
The best is the material situation of households of people working on their own account.
Over 70% of respondents consider it good or rather good in this group.
In the second pole there are household rencists, where the proportion of such responses was only 18%.
The number of children also has a significant impact on the subjective assessment of the material situation of the household.
The worst of them is the single parenting of offspring, of which 32% declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60%, and among childless households is 48.8%.
In these statistics, the 500+ effect is clearly visible.
Before it was launched (in 2016) the worst of its material situation was assessed by parents alone raising offspring and multi-child families (with at least three children).
The improvement of the subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid growth of income, especially from work.
However, this is not all because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good increases faster than real income.
Moreover, there is no clear relationship between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households at the level of the province.
The best ratings are formulated by the residents of the Opole province, where 48.9% of the surveyed consider their situation to be good or rather good.
There are further Lubuskie provinces (47.7 per cent), Silesian (47.6 per cent), Mazowieckie (47.3 per cent) and Western Pomerania (47.1 per cent).
Meanwhile, in Opolski, the governmental income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) was less than 94% of the national average, and 98% in Lubusk.
The highest incomes were in Mazowiecki (120% of the national average) and Silesian (104%).
On average, in Poland, income per person was PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after the price change correction) it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Against the background of previous years, the result is quite low.
In 2016, income per person increased by 7% and a year later by 6.3%.
Although income growth slows down, it also inhibits expenditure growth.
These conversions per person amounted to PLN 1187, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, spending on a person increased by 1.9%, and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Studies on household budgets suggest that the statistical household currently spends 70.1% of its management income, while in 2014 it still exceeded 80%, and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
