Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation for your review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion - such an unusual offer was prepared for the arrival of the German Görlitz.
The actions are designed to help combat the progressive decline in the population of the city.
Görlitz is Germany’s most advanced city.
A beautiful pastel old woman attracts 140,000 tourists every year.
As the Guardian says, “The city is struggling with significant problems.
In Görlitz there are the lowest wages in Germany.
The city also struggles with a constant decline in the number of inhabitants.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them left the west of the country, which turned into a drop in the city population by 25%.
In 2013, it amounted to 54,000 people.
In order to combat the population, officials came up with an idea to start offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
As far as the program was concerned, 150 applications were submitted.
Two-thirds of them were composed by the inhabitants of large cities.
The programme also involved people from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom.
“When we applied, we thought the program was supposed to convince people to move to Görlitz,” one of the project participants said.
“Now we feel it doesn’t matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not,” he added.
The city has seven thousand free apartments, and unemployment is three times higher than the average in the whole country.
Although the city’s authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main objective of the programme is to obtain the opinions of the participants.
The information collected from interviews and questionnaires will help to revive smaller German cities.
“We want to know more about what people need, and if they decide to move, what their motivation was,” said Robert Knippschild.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas for attracting new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a pay programme to promising young professionals for living and working in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in U.S. Tulsa, Oklahoma.
